Comment:
e exists together in a delicate balance. As king, you need to understand that balance and respect all the creatures. From the crawling ant, to the leaping antelope?

But dad, don't we eat the antelope?

Yes, Simba, but let me explain. When we die, our bodies become the grass. And the antelope eat the grass. And so, we are all connected in the great circle of life.
Unless you're a hyena. In which case you don't get to eat.

This theme of food returns again and again. In Be Prepared, the promise Scar makes in order to gain the support of the hyenas is quite explicit: "Stick with me, and you'll never go hungry again!"

The hyenas are overjoyed with this, and chant later in the song "We'll have food! Lots of food! We repeat, endless meat!"

In context, with all the Nazi symbolism, we are meant to see this as a terrible thing. But really, what is the problem with this?

This is the nature of the hyenas' depravity: they want consistent meals. So what? As hunters, why aren't they as entitled to "pick off one of the little, sick ones" as the lions are? Can't they even scavenge carcasses in the Pride Lands?

Do the hyenas commit any crimes at all?

They trespass occasionally into the Pride Lands, apparently. Later on, they eat food. And defend the crowned king.

Shenzi, Banzai, and Ed, of course, are complicit in the plot to kill Mufasa and Simba. Their earlier encounter with Simba in the Elephant Graveyard is more interesting.

The scene begins with Simba and Nala accidentally on purpose sneaking into the Graveyard. They are found by Zazu, who urges a retreat. The three hyenas discover them and threaten them. The cubs run, and are eventually caught and trapped by the hyenas. Mufasa arrives in the nick of time, scattering the hyenas and saving Simba and Nala. We are meant to see the hyenas' attempts to eat Simba and Nala as murder.

Title: The LEGO Batman Movie - Batcave Teaser Trailer [HD]
Comment:
Dear Warner Bros, 

I have to say, I am very disappointed. Not with the movie, it looks alright. My problem is with two things. One, the casting. I do understand that this is a spin off of the Lego movie, but the batman from that movie isn't the best one to make a movie about. Troy Baker would be better, Kevin Conroy would be the best choice. But just because Will Arnet has a deep voice, doesn't mean he's the best choice to play Batman. Sure Kevin Conroy is a serious Batman, I think it'd be funnier to see his Batman in comedic situations. It just takes some clever writing. Which I saw in the Lego movie. The rest of the cast is fine. Except for one. Whatshisname from the hangover. I don't know why you thought he'd be a good joker, but there are lots of better choices for Joker out there. Troy Baker, the legendary Mark Hamill, I know he probably retired, but that didn't stop him from appearing in Arkham Knight. So, my only other problem with this is the music. Rap isn't a good choice.
